body_html:
The problem statement from the tensor flow sample program is:
(train_data, train_labels), (test_data, test_labels) = imdb.load_data(num_words=10000)

Initially, the noted statement generated a DLL error on this statement after successfully running the following statements from the posted tensorflow sample:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow import keras
import numpy as np
print(tf.version)
imdb = keras.datasets.imdb

I installed the recommended C++ Redistributable as advised by the error displayed (17393).

The problem statement then began to generate the following error.
AttributeError: module 'numpy' has no attribute

I removed tensor flow 1.10 and installed tensorflow 1.5 as advised by another posting.

The problem statement then began to generate the following error.

ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'eras' (#16358)

I then tried different versions of tensor flow on the basis that various postings hinted this was a version issue that was reportedly fixed in the next release.

So far, none of the postings on this topic resolve this issue.

body:
The problem statement from the tensor flow sample program is:
(train_data, train_labels), (test_data, test_labels) = imdb.load_data(num_words=10000)

Initially, the noted statement generated a DLL error on this statement after successfully running the following statements from the posted tensorflow sample:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow import keras
import numpy as np
print(tf.version)
imdb = keras.datasets.imdb

I installed the recommended C++ Redistributable as advised by the error displayed (17393).

The problem statement then began to generate the following error.
AttributeError: module 'numpy' has no attribute 

I removed tensor flow 1.10 and installed tensorflow 1.5 as advised by another posting.

The problem statement then began to generate the following error.

ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'eras' (#16358)

I then tried different versions of tensor flow on the basis that various postings hinted this was a version issue that was reportedly fixed in the next release.

So far, none of the postings on this topic resolve this issue.
